  <h2>The Main Factors</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Tank size and compartments.</strong> A larger, multi-compartment tank holds more material and takes longer to service.</li>
    <li><strong>Lid access.</strong> Exposed lids at grade are the easy case; lids buried under soil or a deck add locating and digging.</li>
    <li><strong>Distance and truck access.</strong> Vacuum hoses have practical limits — long drives, gates, slopes and soft ground all matter.</li>
    <li><strong>Time since the last service.</strong> A long-overdue tank holds compacted solids that take more effort to remove.</li>
    <li><strong>Scope.</strong> Removing liquid is one job; fully removing the settled sludge from every compartment is a bigger one.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How to Get a Firmer Quote</h2>
  <p>
    Providers quote confidently when they can picture the job. A request that notes the tank size (if known), whether the lids are exposed, how a truck reaches the tank, and when the system was last serviced gets a much tighter estimate. Exact pricing is always set by the provider — <a href="/request-service/">request septic service</a> with those details and the estimate conversation gets shorter.
  </p>

